e slowed created vast marshland known Everglades. Slower runoff also created accumulation almost 18 feet (5.5 m) peat area. The presence peat deposits, dated 5,000years ago, evidence widespread flooding occurred then.[20] Hydrology[edit] Predevelopment flow direction water Lake Okeechobee Florida Bay Source: U.S. Geological Survey The consistent Everglades flooding fed extensive Kissimmee, Caloosahatchee, Myakka, Peace Rivers central Florida. The Kissimmee River broad floodplain empties directly Lake Okeechobee, 730 square miles (1,900km2) average depth 9 feet (2.7m), vast shallow lake.[21] Soil deposits Everglades basin indicate peat deposited land flooded consistently throughout year. Calcium deposits left behind flooding shorter. The deposits occur areas water rises falls depending rainfall, opposed water stored rock one year next. Calcium deposits present limestone exposed.[22] The area Orlando tip Florida peninsula one point single drainage unit. When rainfall exceeded capacity Lake Okeechobee Kissimmee River floodplain, spilled flowed southwestern direction empty Florida Bay. Prior urban agricultural development Florida, Everglades began southern edge Lake Okeechobee flowed approximately 100 miles (160km), emptying Gulf Mexico. The limestone shelf wide slightly angled instead narrow, deep channel characteristic rivers. The vertical gradient Lake Okeechobee Florida Bay 2 inches (5.1cm) per mile, creating almost 60-mile (97km) wide expanse river travels half mile (0.8km) day.[23] This slow movement broad, shallow river known sheetflow, gives Everglades nickname, River Grass. Water leaving Lake Okeechobee may require months years reach final destination, Florida Bay. The sheetflow travels slowly water typically stored one wet season next porous limestone substrate. The ebb flow water shaped land every ecosystem South Florida throughout Everglades' estimated 5,000years existence. The motion water defines plant communities animals adapt habitats food sources.[24] Climate[edit] Hurricane Charley 2004 moving ashore South Florida's Gulf Mexico coast The climate South Florida located across broad transition zone subtropical tropical climates (Koppen Cf Aw). Like regions climate type, two basic seasons ‚Äì "dry season" (winter) runs November April, "wet season" (summer) runs May October. About 70% annual rainfall south Florida occurs wet season ‚Äì often brief intense tropical downpours. The dry season sees little rainfall dew points humidity often quite low. The dry season severe times, wildfires water restrictions often place. The annual range temperatures south Florida Everglades rather small (less 20¬∞F [11¬∞C]) ‚Äì ranging monthly mean temperature around 65¬∞F (18¬∞C) January 83¬∞F (28¬∞C) July. High temperatures hot wet season (summer) typically exceed 90¬∞F (32¬∞C) across inland south Florida (although coastal locations cooled winds Gulf Mexico Atlantic Ocean), high temperatures dry winter season average 70 79¬∞F (21 26¬∞C). Frost freeze rare across south Florida Everglades; annually coastal cities like Miami Naples report zero days frost, although times decade temperatures may fall 30 40¬∞F (‚àí1 4¬∞C) across South Florida. Annual rainfall averages approximately 62 inches (160cm), Eastern Coastal Ridge receiving majority precipitation area surrounding Lake Okeechobee receiving 48 inches (120cm).[25] Unlike wetland system earth, Everglades sustained primarily atmosphere.[26] Evapotranspiration ‚Äì sum evaporation plant transpiration Earth's land surface atmosphere ‚Äì associated thunderstorms, key mechanism water leaves region. During year unaffected drought, rate may reach 40 inches (100cm) year. When droughts take place, rate may peak 50 inches (130cm), exceed amount rainfall.[27] As water leaves area evaporation groundwater plant matter, activated primarily solar energy, moved wind patterns areas border flow Everglades watershed system. Evapotranspiration responsible approximately 70‚Äì90percent water entering undevelope