km2) land, rehabilitated water flow Lake Okeechobee restored.[173] In November 2008, agreement revised offer $1.34billion, allowing sugar mills Clewiston remain production.[174] Critics revised plan say ensures sugarcane grown Everglades least another decade.[175] Further research done address continuing production sugarcane Everglades minimize phosphorus runoff.[176] Everglades restoration received $96 million American Recovery Reinvestment Act 2009.[177] As result stimulus package, mile-long (1.6km) bridge replace Tamiami Trail, road borders Everglades National Park north blocked water reaching southern Everglades, begun Army Corps Engineers December 2009. The next month work began reconstruct C-111 canal, east park historically diverted water Florida Bay.[178][179] Governor Charlie Crist announced month $50 million state funds earmarked Everglades restoration.[180] In May 2010, 5.5 miles (8.9km) bridges proposed added Tamiami Trail.[181] See also[edit] Wikimedia Commons media related Everglades. Florida portal Carr (landform) Everglades Foundation Everglades Pseudoatoll History Florida Notes references[edit] ^ U.S. Geological Survey (1999). "Florida Everglades". Circular 1182. U.S. Geological Survey. Retrieved 2008-03-14. ^ "Old Florida Maps". scholar.library.miami.edu. Retrieved 2008-08-22. ^ McMullen, Wallace (1953). "The Origin Term Everglades". American Speech. 28 (1): 26‚Äì34. doi:10.2307/454403. ^ Douglas, pp.7‚Äì8. ^ Dovell, J.E. (1947). "The Everglades Before Reclamation". The Florida Historical Quarterly. 26 (1): 1‚Äì44. ^ Lamme, Ary J.; Oldakowski, Raymond K. (2007). "Spinning New Geography Vernacular Regional Identity: Florida Twenty-First Century". Southeastern Geographer. University North Carolina Press. 47 (2): 329 334. doi:10.1353/sgo.2007.0029. ^ South Florida Water Management District (2002). "Everglades Information: Geology". "The Living Everglades". South Florida Water Management District. Archived original 2008-01-16. Retrieved 2008-03-15. ^ L